metadata.name: Dreamcatcher Forest #259
metadata.description:
"Dreamcatcher Forest" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022. The illustration in this work draws inspiration from Native American dreamcatchers, a protective talisman crafted from beautifully intricate patterns of woven thread, built from natural materials & colorful beads.

Dreamcatchers are used to protect dreamers while they sleep. Good dreams are able to slip through the web to meet the sleeper beneath, while bad dreams are trapped and prevented.

- Use the "S" key to save a PNG image.
- Use the "P" key to export a print-quality image.

metadata.name: PIPES #17
metadata.description:
PIPES are its own creatures growing out of an Octree, swirling and twirling towards each's individual destination.  

Features:   
  There are four different flow modes, seven different palettes.   
  PIPES can either be hollow or filled, and there is a small chance the PIPES is drawn in gradient.  

Loading time is about 6s and then it will start to animate. Thank you for your patience.  

Press 'S' to save a high resolution 4800x4800px PNG of the artwork.  

This work is made purely with p5js.

metadata.name: Pobbles #259
metadata.description:
The pobbles are generative blob-rocks: staring in silence, sometimes half-smiling, generally bored. 

‚Ä¢ The pobbles are digital recreations of a series of rock-doodles by S.F.Kislev (my big brother). They are an attempt to capture a specific, singular handwriting, and evolve it using code. 
‚Ä¢ See the original, 2014 handmade version here - https://pobbles.tez.page..
‚Ä¢ Alternative titles considered include Peggles‚Ñ¢, Plops‚Ñ¢, Blobbies‚Ñ¢, Floofs‚Ñ¢, Flintstones‚Ñ¢, Lardies‚Ñ¢, Plumps‚Ñ¢, Fats‚Ñ¢ and Wet-Ones‚Ñ¢. 
‚Ä¢ The pobbles are written entirely in paper.js and p5.js. 
‚Ä¢ The pobbles are an effort to take generative art into the realm of the cute.

metadata.name: Cables and Clouds #120
metadata.description:
Capturing clouds... an old dream of mad scientist... coming true...
But wait... are they real clouds ? Maybe... maybe not...
Is it the real life ?
Is this just fantasy ?

Interaction.
Press h in live mode to list the possibilities.
Key 's'  : Save an image of the output at the current resolution
Key 1-9 : Change resolution
Key 'c' to change color palette
Key 'd' to toggle a special color mode to highlight the different components (and have the number of points used in your specific drawing).

Features.
18 different features displayed (format, color palettes, main elements characteristics, rare elements...).

metadata.name: Shapes on a Plane #328
metadata.description:
‚ÄúShapes on a Plane‚Äù explores imaginary structures and worlds through simple shapes. It‚Äôs intended for small-scale print.

As a kid I was obsessed with Lego, Duplo, wooden building blocks... anything I could make something with.

I‚Äôd spend hours building things, imagining new worlds, new machines, new concepts, then i‚Äôd take them apart and create a whole new idea to explore.

To me, this piece to me is a reminder of that time - many days spent exploring ideas with those simple objects - no care for viability, for marketability, for audiences or business. Just pure fun.

Without this time in my life, I doubt I‚Äôd have found my passion for creating in the way I do today.

metadata.name: Reisiger #73
metadata.description:
We journey through the world, collecting ideas, friendships, loves and experiences. This journey is life and, if you're fortunate, the majority of your journey is good and you eventually meet your Gods knowing that you've lived well.

Reisiger means Traveler in Afrikaans, and this work is meant to portray the hope, joy and diversity of our travail through life.

This piece assembles a simple mesh along a bezier spline of an orbital path around a series of bodies. It uses Newtonian gravity - adequately mangled to make it more interesting - and applies a number of transformations in flight. Hatching and occlusion algorithms are custom, but are developed based on work by Reinder Nijhoff. 

This is a plotter artwork and is intended to be enjoyed both on screen and in print. When printing, choose your pens appropriately - gel pens for dark paper etc, all colours are meant as a suggestion and all versions should look just fine in monochrome if you so choose. If you want an upscaled raster artwork (for regular printing) just add a dpr param to the URL like &dpr=10.

Left-click to download a PNG.
Double-click to download an SVG file ready for plotting.

Licensing: BY-NC-ND see license.md for details.

metadata.name: Everyone needs more Liquidity #185
metadata.description:
Who doesn't?

This piece explores the dynamics of particle physics and liquid in an unbound system. In it, I set up a small space in which a particle system can play, bouncing off obstacles, creating rivers and falls, and responding to various physical constraints.

It is created using a webgl pipeline consisting of, primarily, a GPGPU particle system consisting of 16k particles in motion in real-time. The physics simulation is made possible using a compute shader (not really compute, given webgl, but you get the idea) which records the particles' position, velocity, age, and data to a texture for use by the point program. Each particle is rendered as a semi-transparent radial gradient, adding up to a distance field that is used to render the liquid.

Licensing: CC-BY-NC-ND see LICENCE.md for details

metadata.name: Plottable Thousands #91
metadata.description:
'Thousands' explores the packing of recursive circles and golden angle spirals distributing various particles on a A4 canvas.

A SVG file can be exported (right click save) to plot the piece physically.

You can enjoy the digital version that simulate ink effects and optional, thanks to the utility token decoupling, get a physical one: the digital NFT is the recipe to a plottable art piece, owning it confers the right to plot or request a physical plot from @greweb (https://greweb.me/plots/nft). @greweb would use fountain pens but other plotting artists are free to achieve it with their own materials and ship to collectors ‚Äì as long as NFT is owned at request time.

Code: https://github.com/gre/gre/tree/master/doodles/plottable-thousands

@greweb ‚Äì 2022 ‚Äì tech: WebGL + Rust + WASM ‚Äì CC BY-SA 4.0 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/

metadata.name: Perpetual Oscillations  #43
metadata.description:
Planes expand and contract over time in different rhythms. 

Display notes:
The work is intended to be viewed running live in the browser, and there is no set aspect ratio. The viewer is invited to explore the space and choose their viewpoint. 

Controls:
Left-clicking and dragging - rotate around the center 
right-clicking and dragging - pan around the space 
Scrolling - zoom in and out 
Press b - b-side 
Press o - go back to the origin 
Press 1 to 3 - change the pixel density
Adjusting pixel density or changing the screen size will bring you back to the origin. 

License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

Made with p5.js

metadata.name: Sunset in Paradise #114
metadata.description:
Hundreds of Walkers descend the screen drawing a sky, sea and the sun reflection; creating a twilight scene of a sunset or possibly a sunrise depending on which coast your paradise can be found. 
Features - 32 Palettes 
5 Possible background colors per palette
3 different complexities of sky:
	-Refined - 3 colors (25% chance)
	-Complex - 5 colors (25% chance)
	-Normal - 4 colors (50% chance)
2 possible border colors: 
	Matching the sun color (40% chance) 
	Matching the sea color (60% chance)
2 different stroke thickness: 
	Fine (25% chance) 
	Medium-point (75% chance) 
Different amounts of Walkers for Sky, Sea and reflection.

Made by @p1x3lboy in p5.js
June 2022

metadata.name: NEMA #83
metadata.description:
Unlike us, 
They are minimalist. 
They don't bear the stuff that are not necessary for their life.
They are easily satisfied, not materialistic at all.
They can be both father and mother. and they focus on the next generations.

They are well even when they are alone or with others.
I knew nema 27 yrs ago in my year 1 bio-diversity class.
To celebrate this friendship, I challenge myself to draw nema with only circle() and arc().

100 selected compositions with 1/2/3/4/5 nema-combo. 

Hope you like them as I do.

<S> to export the image
Best experience in large display window.

Built w/ P5js and 10% donation to P5 foundation
